{
  "text": "To test whether the 3\u0408 ORF of RPP14 mRNA was sufficient to complement the yeast dehydratase knockout or point mutations, the corresponding human 3\u0408 ORF was amplified by polymerase chain reaction (PCR) from the cerebellum cDNA library using the primers Hshtd2yEP352f (5\u0408-GCTCTAGAAT-GTTCCCACTAATTTCCAGCCAT-3\u0408) and Hshtd2yEP352r (5\u0408-CCGCTCGAGTCAGGATTTGGAAGCTTCTGG-3\u0408) introducing an XbaI restriction site 5\u0408 of the initiation ATG and an XhoI restriction site 3\u0408 of the stop codon, respectively. The digested PCR product was ligated into the S. cerevisiae expression vector pYE352-CTA1 [CITATION_1] , replacing the CTA1 ORF and resulting in plasmid pYE352-Hshtd2. Plasmids pYE352-Hshtd2, pYE352-htd2, and pYE352-Cta1 were transformed into yeast strains htd2-1 and \u232chtd2 on SC-Ura \u03ea with 2% glucose. The transformants were moved to synthetic complete plates with 3% glycerol and grown at 30\u00b0C for 6 -7 days.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "6646064"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "6646064": {
      "title": "Changing stereochemistry for a metabolic pathway in vivo. Experiments with the peroxisomal beta-oxidation in yeast",
      "abstract": "Abstract The biosphere is inherently built of chiral molecules, and once their metabolism is established, the stereochemical course of the reactions involved is seen to remain highly conserved. However, by replacing the yeast peroxisomal multifunctional enzyme (MFE), which catalyzes the second and third reactions of \u03b2-oxidation of fatty acids via D-3-hydroxyacyl-CoA intermediates, with rat peroxisomal MFE, which catalyzes the same reactions via L-3-hydroxy intermediates, it was possible to change the chiralities of the intermediates in a major metabolic pathway in vivo. Both stereochemical alternatives allowed the yeast cells to grow on oleic acid, implying that when the \u03b2-oxidation pathways evolved, the overall function was the determining factor for the acquisition of MFEs and not the stereospecificities of the reactions themselves."
    }
  }
}